segments.text: Trying to figure out, trying to figure out, trying to figure out what has gone wrong with this machine hoping that everything is now working.
Okay, we're talking about your freshman football time.
Manning Smith was the...
He was the head freshman football coach, and he used mostly, if not all, graduate students.
For example, there was a guy here named Dog Dawson.
Do you remember him?
Well, I remember him.
Well, he had played varsity football the year before, but he was like a five-year student.
And he was the...
assistant, a guy named Bill Buchanan was.
So mostly all of them, Jim Connection was one.
They were the coaches.
All we did as freshmen was just gun fodder.
Gun fodder for the varsity.
And you all played five games, six games?
Yeah, we played Allen Academy and we played Arlington.
And we played probably five or six games, yeah.
The
Hey, the Varsity Stars, let's see, Kimbrough was gone, wasn't he?
Kimbrough was gone.
The Varsity Stars were Mosier.
Knatzer.
Pugh.
No, Pugh was gone.
Pugh was gone.
Bill Knatzer from Denison.
Yeah.
Jim Sterling from... Oh, yeah.
...Pex O'Connor.
Mm-hmm.
Um...
Whiskey Cure was one of them.
And you all ran offensively, what was the formation?
Single wing, double wing, and box.
Pete hadn't come in yet.
And you ran, pass plays would be one out of four.
TC is the only one that threw much of the ball.
The workouts normally began about what?
Describe a typical workout.
not on a Monday or Friday.
We would go out and first they'd loosen up in calisthenics, which they don't do much anymore, they do stretching.
We'd do calisthenics, then we'd break down into offense would go over and rush home.
Line blocking, the punters would punt, the pass receivers and the quarterback would practice catching and throwing the ball, and then they'd
Forrest would call up, we need so many guys, they'd send us over there.
Haskell, Bear Bryant did a lot of things, but I think what he did mostly, he changed the whole routine of workouts.
He went to the county fair times.
We didn't have that before.
He had a group over here doing this, a group doing this.
Now, for example, if we had blocking, one-on-one blocking linemen, we'd have one-on-one blocking everybody that's standing watching.
Mm-hmm.
or if we had punting or pass, you see, he broke it down to where everybody was working all the time.
And that dad that got out into all the high schools, that was the biggest change, I think, that and defense, pursuit and defense.
Used to, if you got through the first line at the last green, you wasn't going to get tackled by a line.
But Brian got pursuit.
What kind of defense did y'all run?
What they did in those days, believe it or not, the center would come up the line of skinnings
And he'd wait seven-man line, six-man line, five-man line.
The defense set up.
Long time before the huddle got up or what they don't do anymore.
So they knew what you could do.
And then whatever defense he called, that changed.
what kind of blocking you were going to do on the guy.
And they always did two on one blocking.
High and low.
Hit them high, hit them low, hit them low, let them go, that kind of stuff.
It was not this brush blocking or just getting them out of the way.
You had to put your man on the ground, which was very difficult to do.
And there were, what, six or seven varsity coaches?
Yeah, probably, yeah.
Bill James, Uncle Bill James, he was the line coach.
And one of these guys, he's kind of like a man named Bill Lance.
Uncle Bill had come here from Texas.
And he was the one that owned Camp Stewart, this boy's camp down in Kerrville, the famous camp down there.
That was his camp.
So he just coached and he wasn't even faculty.
And then we had some others there.
I think what happened here, the war was on.
And one day a guy would be here and the next day he's gone.
We'd have students one day and they'd be gone.
So they kept moving them all out.
Older coaches like Norton and Uncle Bill don't always stay here.
Marty Caroll.
Where were you when you heard the news on December 7th?
I was walking back from D. Warefield House.
One Sunday, I'd been at a clean basket.
Did somebody tell you or what?
I guess somebody said we're in war.
Of course, we knew the war was coming.
But they said to bomb Pearl Harbor.
Nobody knew where Pearl Harbor was.
Well, so what's Pearl Harbor?
And where did you, after you heard that, what did you do?
Where did you go?
Well, I went on back to my dorm and went out to eat.
We just said, we weren't shocked, I don't think, because we kind of felt like we were going to get in the war.
But we didn't know.
We were so dumb.
We didn't know what war was.
We'd never been in war.
We didn't know what the aftermath was going to be.
And a lot of guys got excited.
You know, gung-ho.
I want to go.
I want to go.
I want to go.
They didn't know the horrors of war.
All right.
Let's go back to this freshman year.
Other than being a room orderly and so forth, what were some other hazings?
that you endured your freshman year?
Well, I don't know if you call that.
We couldn't walk on the sidewalk.
We had to walk in the street.
If we were walking down the street and we saw a member of our outfit with somebody, we had to go over and stop.
You know, I'm outtie.
I'm fish well, so-and-so, so-and-so, so-and-so.
Or if we were walking down the street and we didn't speak to somebody, say, I didn't speak to you and you were B Infantry, you didn't eat my butt out.
You tore my outfit.
Say, oh.
They would call me.
We didn't, they, upperclassmen did not mess with other people's freshmen.
We walked in the street.
Lots of times we couldn't eat until all the upperclassmen had been served.
Sometimes we'd have to eat under the table.
And what we'd do, we'd hang around the upperclassmen.
Like that second meal, you saw my wife go.
Then we could go get kush off of these adjoining tables, but we couldn't get it.
Now you ate in Duncan.
We ate in Duncan.
Had separate tables.
All right.
You athletes...
Did you all eat at the same time as everyone else?
Yes, same time.
And you ate the same food?
A little bit better, maybe.
For example, they'd set a crate of milk at the end of our table.
We could make that.
And then we had our after-meal games in there, too, which was, you know, pretty good.
We ate the same food, but we got a little bit, maybe a few extras in there.
And as a freshman, you had one roommate?
Had one roommate, a guy named Vernon Bell, too.
And so y'all learned all of the Aggie lingo.
We had to learn all that just like everybody else.
Just like everybody else.
All right.
Do you remember any notable freshman, any notable pranks your freshman year?
Yes.
Air out.
You know what air out is?
Sure.
Okay, we had air out where they would come through the dorm at midnight or so and air out.
Well, you climbed out the windows and you were out for the rest of the night.
And we'd go down there to the flying center, where the golf course is now.
We'd have to sleep down there.
Or one of the things is the drownouts were terrible.
What they'd do, they'd take a Coke box, the end of a Coke box.
You know, it's got those little 12 things in it.
They'd cut a notch in it like that.
And they'd come in and throw a bucket of water in your bed and then shut your door.
And they'd hook that over the doorknob, and you couldn't open your door.
So all the time, the upperclassmen were having the freshmen go down, drown out some children.
And of course we got caught, we got in trouble, but the upperclassmen,
They're the ones doing it.
We did whatever they said.
Grabbed boots for us all the time, stuff like that.
We could not stay on our beds at all in the daytime.
We couldn't sit on our beds.
Cesar Blue would let me come over to his room.
He was senior and an officer.
He'd let me take a nap on his bed sometimes.
But you couldn't sit on your bed.
If the upperclassmen came in, of course, you had to jump to a kitchen, stuff like that.
We just lived in horror all the time.
But it became a game.
All right, now, what outfit were you in?
I was in A infantry.
And that was not an... No, I'm sorry.
First year was F infantry.
And that was not an athletic outfit?
It was an athletic outfit.
Oh, it was?
Yeah, when I was a freshman.
Did y'all have a nickname that's tellable in mixed company?
No, they didn't do that in those days.
Oh, really?
I don't remember any of them being like that.
When I was a sophomore, we lived with our outfields.
We were just not all military.
But like they do now, they have these nicknames.
I don't know.
Today, there may be A through B infantry.
We had A through M infantry.
That's all there is in the Army.
Three regiments.
We had A through M
field artillery.
We had coastal artillery, we had the jocks, we had ordnance, and maybe one other.
We didn't have an air force in those days.
Was there any of those Army specialties that had a higher prestige?
I don't think so.
I'll tell you the meanest bunch of the whole damn place was the band.
The band?
Oh, yeah.
They'd fight and drop a hat.
Is that right?
They'd go by.
I think a band lived over in Walton, I mean, Longford.
And Josh would go by there and make some derogatory of the band.
That's all that.
The band was tough.
All right, now, normally you were up at what island?

daylight i guess i'll get six o'clock six o'clock probably and then uh breakfast and so you're in classes pretty well all morning yes all right then uh this is during football season yeah then noon meal then what what time did what did you do between lunch and football practice
But we went to classes in the afternoon until about 3 o'clock.
Now, Stalin's did something different.
Then you went straight to practice.
Then after practice, we'd go over to Francis Hall on the campus and have what we called a youth college school practice.
Coach Norton would come in and...
and we'd have about an hour of talking about what's going on.
They don't do that more, they do it now before, but we'd do it at night over there.
And so we got home around eight o'clock, 8.30, best I can recall.
And then typically did y'all really do homework in your room?
Yeah, they had compulsory study, not as probably strict as they all do now, but from like seven to nine,
There was no monkey business going on, or seven to 10.
Nobody, no, that didn't bother me.
Now, was it according to the rules for you to be out of your room after 10 o'clock?
We didn't get out after 10 o'clock.
So when you all slipped out of the dormitory, that was rare?
I never slipped out.
Had nowhere to go, had no way to go.
There was no cars, see?
Okay.
But you also, you had to wear your uniform until you got 50 miles off campus.
Mm-hmm.
So we had nowhere to go.
I don't even remember going to a home.
I don't remember going past George Bush South.
I don't remember going to Northgate.
We just lived over in the little old bitty world of our own.
All right.
That first year you came in September.
When did you go home?
I went home Christmas.
You didn't go home Thanksgiving?
No.
We played ball on Thanksgiving.
Now the second year I went home Thanksgiving because we played in Texas.
Yeah.
So you went home Christmas.
The war is then underway.
Yeah.
You come back.
And you're majoring in what?
Aggie.
What?
I'm glad you asked that question.
My friend, Darius Moser, again.
I came here.
In those days, we had no counselors at all.
I came from a good school.
I did what I wanted to in high school.
Big shots and all that junk.
So I told Darish, they didn't have PE, that's what I said.
I said, Darish, I ain't very smart, and I can't afford to bust out of here.
I'd be embarrassed to death.
He said, hell, take Ag Eco.
Nobody would bust out of Ag Eco.
In those days, the only job at Ag Eco was county agents.
I didn't know a thing from a cucumber.
Was there a major that a whole bunch of athletes took?
Well, some of them took, we had some engineering, we had some under two-bit medicine, but most of them were under agriculture, ag-eco, most of them.
Was there anybody on the football team then when you got here who was a notable brain?
Percy Anderson.
Jennings Anderson from Burnley, Texas.
You know that?
He was very smart.
He was probably the smartest guy in our class.
And my roommate was a smart old boy, Vernon Bell.
We had some smart guys, yeah.
But I wasn't one of them.
Let's see.
Who were some of the, as you look back on your years, who were some of the memorable teachers, advisors, counselors?
Well, Dr. Dan Russell was.
He was their bachelor.
He loved athletes.
Gosh, what's his name?
I had it just on the tip of my tongue, who later became vice chancellor.
Odie Butler.
Odie, okay.
Yeah, he was teaching.
I think he just started.
He taught us over there.
Ray Putnam, do you remember Ray?
He was one of our teachers over there.
Screaming Al Ness was one of our teachers.
And some of the others I don't remember too well.
All right.
Was there anybody you went to for advice about grade courses or anything else?
No.
They didn't tell us to.
Did you go to the YMCA activities?
No.
On Saturday night, what did you and your buddies do for fun?
We'd go to the free picture show up at Sammy Hall.
That was it.
That's the only place we had to go.
They had a campus theater.
And we go in there, well, freshman had to sit over inside where the upperclassmen were sitting.
I was scared to go there in the first place.
They had Franklins out on 61, but we had no way to get out.
I went there one time.
We didn't go anywhere.
We'd stick our head out the thing.
We got the screaming.
Now, was this county dry?
Yes, it was dry.
Totally dry for beer?
Yes.
They had that place out up the bridge.
You went to Whiskey Bridge.
Yeah, Whiskey Bridge.
All right.
Uh, so, uh, Hardlickers wasn't there yet.
Yes, Hardlickers was there.
Okay.
But I didn't ever go to Hardlickers.
Right.
Uh, now, he sold beer, didn't he?
I don't know.
Well, on Thursdays we drilled.
Okay.
Everybody drilled.
Mm-hmm.
And we wore a white coverall, see, with that seal on the back.
I like to use them for labs, too.
I wish I had some.
And we'd march down Wellborn to Hardlickers, and then we'd cut right and go through the woods.
Most of it was just walking through.
Now, where was Hardlickers?
About where that Coffee Bridge store is?
About where that Chinese store is.
I mean, that hamburger place in the Coffee Bridge going down the Wellborn Road?
Well, best I remember, you know where the south side apartments are over where the poor folks live?
Yeah.
I think it was right there.
right in that area.
I only went in at one time.
The thing I remember, they had these huge tables that everybody from year one had cut the initials into.
Was there any place you heard of anywhere else in town where legally or illegally people could buy liquor?
I didn't drink and I wasn't interested.
And there was no red light area that I've ever heard of?
No.
They talk about these kids going down here to
to the chicken ranch?
Yeah, but I didn't know that was there.
I didn't hear about that until after chicken ranch was no more.
I don't even know how true that is.
But we did have drinking.
Now, the guy said beer in the dorms, I guarantee you.
Okay.
But I don't know where they got it.
But it was serious if they got caught, was it?
Well, I guess.
I don't know.
They said you don't drink, but, you know, I don't know.
I never had it come up.
Did y'all
and youth athletes as freshmen.
Y'all didn't have to fall out before supper.
In March Inn?
In March Inn.
Yes, we did.
We did?
We did our thing in the core.
See, we were right there in the core.
You couldn't tell us and anybody else.
No, but I thought that y'all would have been practicing still.
Oh, I see what you're talking about.
After football season, we did.
Yeah.
No, we came in after they'd already eaten.
Yeah, we got in there late.
Okay.
All right, then once the season's over, y'all are doing exactly everything everybody else is doing.
Among your freshman recruit colleagues, did many of them drop out of school?
Yes, quite a few.
One of the biggest disappointments I had, when they started breaking teams down as freshmen,
I think they had, I said 100, I know there's over 100 guys, and I think they broke down about 10 teams, and I still hadn't been picked.
Well, I was just really upset.
I was scared because I didn't want to have to leave here.
So I know that later on it turned out a lot of the guys left, and that was early and all.
But, yeah, we had guys leaving every day.
Every day people left.
Now, the varsity then had about how many on scholarship?
Oh, gosh.
Let me look here.
I've got a picture of it.
Let's look.
They have about 100.
So about 50.
By and large, as far as you know, we're almost all of them on full scholarship.
As far as I know.
You know why they only need 50?
Oh, everybody played one way.
Both ways.
They played both ways.
And you freshmen, about how many were on scholarship?
Do you know?
I have no idea.
Now, was it a secret when you were a student?
Did...
Did folks like you, were you hesitant to say, oh, I'm in scholarship?
No, it was no secret.
I just don't know.
I figured everybody was.
But some of them might be partial.
I don't really know.
No, it was no secret.
It was public knowledge.
And you took, what kind of academic level did you take that first year?
I don't know, but I would guess around 12, 14, somewhere 15.
Took a basic course.
Were there any that you remember that first year that were either unusually easy or unusually hard?
Algebra was unusually hard.
I had to take it twice.
Okay.
Very hard.
And what did you wear to class?
I wore a uniform.
I didn't even have to be in clothes then.
And what was your attitude about class attendance?
I didn't cut class, I was afraid to.
Now here's what I did do, as you may or may not know, they had this auditorium and they checked roll by the inter-seat number, you know, I guess I still stand.
The last time, Mosier sent me to sit up in his seat.
He didn't come in the instructor, he just, he wasn't even paying attention to what it was, the seat was covered, so Mosier got credit for it.
I did that a lot.
Okay.
And he was a senior?
He was a senior, big dog.
He's a big dog.
Okay.
But you couldn't send anybody to sit in your seat.
I didn't cut class.
I don't think I ever cut class.
All right.
As you look back on your courses, which courses do you remember most fondly that you enjoyed?
Speech.
Speech.
I loved it.
Who was Dr. Doak?
And public speaking particularly.
I took that course, and I just loved it.
But that got me, oh, I was nervous.
I mean, a little scared kid.
And they made us get, the greatest thing about coming to A&M to me has two things.
They made you introduce yourself.
And you still do it today.
You just automatically, nothing here takes me more than to talk to somebody and they don't tell me who it is.
They made you speak to everybody.
And they made you, and we were not like that when we came here.
We were scared.
And we were ignorant of that.
And that thing, that personality just came out more like that.
Because you were an oddball if you didn't, and you're going to get in all kinds of trouble if you didn't.
So you had to learn that.
They don't have it today.
Did you ever hitchhike?
All the time.
And where, if you're going to go home to Stephenville, where did you catch a ride from?
Eastgate.
You know that story about lining up.
I understand that grades and class rank, none of those matter.
Who got there first.
Who got there first.
And if you were coming at 50th in line, you could put your suitcase down, go pick you up, come back, and they would move it up.
And that you always were in uniform.
Always.
Never assigned.
No.
Tell them where you were going.
No.
So normally it would take you about how long to get from here to Steubenville?
Well, one time I left here in the afternoon.
I got there the next morning at 6 o'clock.
I got hung up in Clifton, Texas.
What route would you normally take?
Well, I used to, I'd go from here to Waco.
And Waco, I'd go up to Clifton, Valley Mills, Iredale, Ico.
But there was no traffic through.
I found out later it's quicker if I go from here to Fort Worth.
And then go out from Fort Worth.
And I'd go that way.
Did you ever have any negative experience?
Never.
Never?
People looked for you.
We had stations that they'd go look for you.
And, of course, the uniform was unusual in those days, and anybody in uniform was an Aggie, so everybody knew who the Aggies were.
And do you have any fond experiences?
Well, I have one that happened one time.
I was hitchhiking in Stephenville, and I got hung up in Clifton, Texas, early in the afternoon.
And I remember I was standing on the corner there, and this little old lady came by me and saw me, and she went on downtown.
You've been to Clifton, haven't you?
And she came back six o'clock and I was still standing there.
And she stopped and said, honey, why don't you come home and suffer with me?
She thought I finally got a ride and a pickup.
And he took me to Glen Rose, which is out of the way.
And I spent most of the night there.
And that's when I got home at six o'clock the next morning.
It took about 13 hours or something.
But yeah, we moved pretty fast.
And you and your buddies never worried about your safety?
Never thought about it.
That's what I heard.
We had to talk.
Our rules were you talk to your host if they want to talk.
If they don't talk, you don't talk, and you do not go to sleep.
And that was S.O.T.
And I understand that sometimes the car would stop and take only one person.
And other times, they'd take as many people as they had seats.
We had trucks.
We had flatbed trucks load them up.
I've seen 40 guys get on one truck.
Oh, my.
Now, that wiped the line out.
Oh, my.
That was what was really great.
Now, was Eastgate the starting point both for going north and south?
That's right.
You didn't upstream, you know.
Yeah, yeah.
You went out there if you're going to hitchhike.
Yeah.
Okay.
Now, there must have been a special place, say, in Fort Worth.
There was, and it was in Waco.
Okay.
And there was one in Abilene.
There was all over the state of Texas.
One in Austin, one in Houston.
And I've never heard of anybody in any of those other towns trying to play any pranks on the hitchhiker.
I never had any pranks.
It was just something that everybody talked about.
The people loved the Aggies.
They took a little poor little lonesome boy down there by himself.
I'd go home, and my mother and her old friends, they'd tell so sorry about you.
You know how scroungy some of us were.
Now, were there midnight y'all practices that freshman year?
Yes, yes.
All right, and did you have any dates to those?
No.
So you went by yourself.
Went to Houston.
I remember Houston, we went down there when I was a freshman to play Rice, and they had it at the Rice Hotel.
Oh, my God.
And the L leaders were on top of the canopy and they called the fire department out and broke it up and they dispersed the whole crowd with the fire hose.
Oh boy.
I've been in that one.
Alright, was that a court trip?
That's a court trip.
Okay.
And did you, freshman athletes, did you all march?
No, not a court trip.
Okay, no.
Did the Tessies come down here?
Yeah, but I never saw any of them.
Now, I remember when I was a sophomore, see, I was nearly married to my first wife.
And as a sophomore, we lived over in 12, and I remember that 10 was emptied out, and these girls came in there for a dance, you know, where they'd put the curtains up and all.
But I don't remember.
I never heard the testes when I was here.
But I was already taken.
Yeah.
All right, that freshman year, do you remember muster?
No.
Let's see.
Oh, did you and your buddies ever turn on the radio to listen to President Roosevelt's speeches?
Yes, some.
Particularly that Monday speech.
Yeah, yeah.
Did you listen to that one?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Infamous.
Yeah, where were you?
I was up in the dorm.
In the dorm?
Okay.
The thing that impressed me about President Roosevelt, I couldn't understand how a man could talk and never say uh or oh.
I didn't realize he was reading those speeches.
I thought he was fantastic.
Oh, no, no more from me.
Thank you.
No.
A glass of water.
No, I'm doing mine.
As a country kid, see, I was born in 31.
He was the first person I ever heard on the radio do formal things.
So I thought he sounded so polished, so articulate.
Oh, yeah, I couldn't understand anything.
So skillful.
Yeah.
Let's see.
During that freshman year, what were the highest prestige student?
Band commander, corps commander, what?
Corps commander, definitely.
Corps commander.
In those days, most guys, as you know, you know all this, worked away through school.
Our battalion commander was also a yell leader, but he also worked in the kitchen as a kitchen employee, working his way through.
Did you ever hear a guy, Buck, did you ever hear an old boy named Buck come over here?
Where Joe Hedrick lives.
Franklin, this guy's name was Buck.
He played football here.
He's the one that beat up the Corps of Commanders.
What's his first name?
I don't know.
Well, I won't get into it.
Anyway, he's dead now.
All right.
At the end of that freshman year, what did you do that summer?
I went to work with Burt Pop.
New London, Texas.
Doing what?
Rough making in the oil field.
What'd you make?
75 cents.
Was that good pay?
That was good if you're going to make that kind of work.
We had some guys that made a little bit more of that, but they worked on tanks, building those huge tanks, and I wasn't strong enough to handle those.
And you were there at New London near the site of that explosion?
Yeah, we had a camp right nearby.
And then you're back in the fall of 42.
And it's getting hairier and hairier.
And let's see, the Kitty Corps was not next year.
That was next year.
All right, so that by and large, your sophomore year, you play, what position did you play?
You were running back for first team, second team?
Well, I alternated on first team.
With?
Leo Daniels and Brian Taylor.
Now, we played, I played safety on the second, on the defense.
And did y'all make any notable trips that year?
We went to Oklahoma.
We went to Carpus.
We played Carpus Naval Station at Doe Rollins.
Doe Rollins was coaching.
They beat the car out of us.
All these old college kids.
Yeah.
and we went to LSU.
That's the first time I'd ever eaten on a train.
Now, y'all picked up the train here?
We picked the train up here, and we drove it, rode it to Houston, and then we got off, got on sleep, and went to Baton Rouge.
Yeah, went to Baton Rouge.
We spent the night and got up early and came back to Houston and then switched to the train that comes through here regularly and came on back home.
That was usually the routine.
Now, how many times had you been on the train before this?
Well, I was in the National Guard when I was 14, so I'd go wherever somebody came.
But it was not a fancy train like that.
When we played Oklahoma, we'd ride the train up there.
When we played Arkansas, we'd ride the train up to Muskogee.
We'd get off and then bus in because you couldn't get to the train.
How was being a sophomore different from being a freshman?
Oh, we thought we were big shots.
And we felt it.
And we got out all the hell that we had to go through as freshmen.
